What's Next for Hyperliquid?

Sunny Shi

Feb 7, 2025 ⋅  12 min read

Key Insights

  • Hyperliquid has cultivated a high-value, recurring user base of performance-driven traders, positioning itself as the only alternative L1 with a clearly defined core cohort.
  • By adding new assets like BTC to the native Hyperliquid spot market, the product gains a significant new growth vertical that can help accelerate progress towards displacing CEXs.
  • The HyperEVM broadens Hyperliquid’s scope beyond trading, enabling a new wave of third-party DeFi applications while maintaining the efficiency of its onchain order book.
  • The Assistance Fund (AF) creates a structurally embedded value accrual mechanism by reinvesting trading revenues into continuous HYPE accumulation, a feature lacking in most DeFi protocols.

Introduction

Hyperliquid’s token genesis event (TGE) was a resounding success, as we had predicted in our pre-TGE valuation report. Since its late-November debut, HYPE’s value has rapidly ascended, reaching a peak fully diluted valuation (FDV) of over $35 billion before retracing to around $23 billion at the time of writing. This trajectory has quickly positioned Hyperliquid among the top 25 crypto assets by market capitalization.

Looking ahead, Hyperliquid stands at the precipice of several pivotal developments—each with the potential to fundamentally reshape its utility, market positioning, and long-term value capture. In this report, we dissect three of the most significant near-term catalysts for the emerging L1: a major expansion to its native spot market, the introduction of the HyperEVM, and the sustained impact of the Assistance Fund.

To learn more about our views and early coverage on Hyperliquid, read our previous reports on the protocol here and here.

Catalyst #1 - Expanding the Spot Market

To progress towards becoming “Onchain Binance”, Hyperliquid has to continue to improve the value proposition of its native spot orderbook. In January, Hyperliquid’s monthly spot volumes represented just 3.3% of perp volumes, with the large majority of spot volumes tied to HYPE trading activity.

Bringing Spot BTC to Hyperliquid’s Orderbook

For now, spot trading on Hyperliquid has been confined to a limited selection of native assets, primarily HYPE, speculative memecoins, and a handful of protocol-backed listings such as RAGE. This restricted asset scope has inherently constrained the platform’s ability to attract serious spot traders seeking exposure to major cryptocurrencies that are not native to Hyperliquid.

We believe that in the near future, expansions can be made to the Hyperliquid L1 to enable direct spot BTC trading on Hyperliquid’s orderbook. From an end-user perspective, trading BTC on Hyperliquid’s spot market should be as seamless as trading HYPE, reinforcing Hyperliquid’s broader ambition to challenge and displace CEXs as the premier venue for both spot and derivatives trading. This marks the first step in a broader revamp of the spot market, with Hyperliquid evolving into a one stop shop to facilitate liquid, onchain trading for any asset.

The Opportunity / Implications

In 2024, spot volumes across the top 10 CEXs accounted for approximately 30% of perpetual trading volumes. Given sufficient asset listings and market maker adoption, Hyperliquid could follow a similar trajectory, capturing 20-30% in additional trading volume as its spot market matures and liquidity deepens.

With an expanded spot market, Hyperliquid will be well-positioned to establish itself as a leading venue for onchain BTC spot trading. Over the past 30 days, our datasets estimate that WBTC and cbBTC trading volumes on major DEXs exceeded $33 billion, while Hyperliquid’s BTC perps recorded $63 billion in volume. If Hyperliquid can achieve 30% spot volume penetration relative to perps, it could capture over 50% of the total volumes currently trading alternative BTC tokens within DeFi. However, onboarding spot BTC volumes will likely take time, as CEX-only users have fewer competing alternatives for purchasing spot assets, whereas onchain participants have an array of DEXs to choose from.

Future enhancements—such as enabling BTC as coin margin for perps or integrating it within the HyperEVM DeFi ecosystem—will further strengthen the incentives to hold and trade spot assets directly on Hyperliquid. The opportunity for Hyperliquid to establish itself as a primary source of onchain price discovery for BTC, an asset long constrained by poor mainnet trading UX, is significant.

The Future - Trade any Asset on Hyperliquid

Beyond BTC, by enabling other assets like SOL, ETH, and even RWAs to trade on Hyperliquid’s central-limit orderbook (CLOB), Hyperliquid can strengthen the platform’s value proposition for high-value spot traders. We expect that the introduction of external assets into the native spot market will drive a significant uptick in trading activity through:

  • New traders migrating to Hyperliquid to trade majors on a highly performant onchain CLOB.
  • Existing Hyperliquid perp DEX users shifting their spot trading activity to the platform, consolidating their execution venue.
  • Frontends and aggregators tapping into Hyperliquid’s liquidity to meet end-user demand for BTC, SOL, and ETH.
  • Increased volume across non-native tokens and long-tail alts, which can now list on the spot market alongside Hyperliquid’s perp offerings.

The path will be cleared for Hyperliquid to become the best venue to get exposure to any crypto-asset. The protocol will be able to deliver superior execution vs. fragmented AMM DEXs, and a more agile approach to listings vs. slower moving CEXs. Unlike other chains, Hyperliquid has already onboarded sophisticated market makers familiar with their orderbook and APIs and cultivated a highly engaged trading community.

With strong market maker participation, Hyperliquid can provide leading onchain execution for any new spot listings. In this scenario, listings on Hyperliquid’s spot orderbook could serve as major liquidity-enhancing events for new tokens, fundamentally reshaping their onchain market dynamics. The formula becomes clear: list on Hyperliquid, tap into deep orderbook liquidity, and become more accessible to a cohort of high-value onchain traders.

Catalyst #2 - Introducing the HyperEVM

To advance toward becoming a full Layer-1, Hyperliquid is preparing to integrate the HyperEVM into its existing architecture. Currently, the Hyperliquid stack is built exclusively around its native L1, which serves as the foundation for its perps and spot orderbook, secured by the HyperBFT consensus. The introduction of the HyperEVM marks a pivotal step in Hyperliquid’s evolution, transforming it from a suite of trading products to a general purpose blockchain and alternative Layer-1.

The HyperEVM - Growing a General Purpose L1

The HyperEVM will introduce a general-purpose EVM network as an integrated component of the blockchain state, secured by the same HyperBFT consensus that underpins Hyperliquid’s existing infrastructure.

By incorporating an EVM execution layer into the Hyperliquid stack, the network creates a dedicated environment for third-party developers to build composable applications, all while maintaining the efficiency and competitive edge of its orderbook-driven products. In effect, Hyperliquid’s consensus will support two distinct but interoperable virtual machines (VMs) running in parallel within a unified state.

Through this separation, Hyperliquid ensures that transactions on the native component remain optimized for performance, preserving the current transaction sequencing characteristics which prioritize market maker cancels. It also mitigates the dilutive impact of general-purpose transactions from the HyperEVM, preventing them from competing with orderbook activity for native blockspace—an issue that will persist with DeFi applications trying to support high-frequency trading on a busy general purpose blockchain.

Additionally, this architecture allows the Hyperliquid team to retain certain permissioned characteristics on the native L1, ensuring that core trading infrastructure remains secure and performant, while simultaneously granting permissionless access for third-party teams to build freely on the HyperEVM. This dual-model approach balances performance, security, and open development, positioning Hyperliquid as a unique hybrid between an optimized trading protocol and a fully extensible Layer-1 ecosystem.

The HyperEVM is designed to seamlessly interact with the Hyperliquid L1. Precompiles allow EVM contracts to read real-time data from the L1 and execute actions on it in a structured, sequential manner. ERC20 tokens on the EVM can also launch an interoperable native spot asset on the L1, allowing users to trade with deep liquidity on the L1 order book while also utilizing the same asset across EVM applications. The result is a new class of onchain DeFi applications on the HyperEVM that can access and integrate Hyperliquid’s native orderbook liquidity within their functions.

A few examples of these DeFi applications might include:

  • A lending protocol that routes liquidations through the spot order book.
  • An AI agent protocol that executes Hyperliquid trades via smart contracts.
  • An options protocol that dynamically hedges exposure using Hyperliquid perps.
  • A delta-neutral stablecoin product, replicating the Ethena model entirely onchain.
  • A protocol token that lists on Hyperliquid’s spot market while extending its functionality through a corresponding ERC-20 asset on the HyperEVM.

These protocols benefit from direct proximity to Hyperliquid’s order book, which remains fully onchain and accessible within the EVM environment. While we have previously compared Hyperliquid’s HyperEVM to Binance’s BSC chain, the level of interoperability between the order book and the EVM creates a fundamentally more synergistic ecosystem. Unlike in the BSC ecosystem, where Binance’s offchain order book remains entirely siloed, the HyperEVM can directly leverage Hyperliquid’s liquidity and order flow, reinforcing its competitive edge as the first true onchain CLOB with a composable EVM application layer.

The Opportunity / Implications

From a market perspective, the HyperEVM has the potential to significantly rerate HYPE’s valuation ceiling, delivering a substantial reappraisal of its long-term value. We believe that while investors are accounting for some potential execution risk, a meaningful portion of capital has yet to fully price in the broader implications of this upgrade.

Should the HyperEVM prove successful, Hyperliquid stands to benefit across multiple dimensions:

  • Definitive classification as a Layer-1, removing any ambiguity around its positioning in the blockchain landscape.
  • Higher TVL, driven by the introduction of a diverse set of new DeFi applications leveraging Hyperliquid’s trading infrastructure.
  • Increased orderbook volumes, as DeFi protocols on the HyperEVM generate additional organic order flow.
  • Expanded token diversity, with the introduction of native USDC and other ERC-20 assets.

This transition represents more than just an architectural expansion—it is a fundamental evolution in how Hyperliquid is perceived and valued within the broader market.

For context, despite zero external DeFi applications contributing to its DeFiLlama TVL Hyperliquid already commands approximately ~60% of the total TVL generated by 52 protocols on SUI. With the launch of the HyperEVM, Hyperliquid is poised to unlock key comparative metrics that will significantly enhance its positioning as a competitive alternative L1. By broadening its scope and enabling a diverse DeFi landscape, Hyperliquid’s appeal as a chain will become far more compelling

Catalyst #3 - The Assistance Fund

A portion of Hyperliquid’s trading fees is allocated to the Assistance Fund (AF), which has functioned as a consistent buyer of HYPE since its inception. To date, the AF has accumulated over 14 million HYPE from the open market, representing approximately 4.3% of the circulating supply, with holdings now valued at over $360 million.

Going forward, the continued operation of the AF ensures that Hyperliquid can convert protocol trading volumes and fee revenues into sustained buying pressure and supply control for the HYPE token.

The Opportunity / Implications

Over the past two weeks, the Assistance Fund (AF) has been accumulating HYPE at an average rate of ~$1.7 million per day. At this pace, the fund is on track to generate ~$620 million in annualized buying pressure, fueled by protocol activity.

We see this as a community-aligned mechanism for value redistribution, ensuring that HYPE holders directly benefit from the sustained monetization of Hyperliquid’s revenue-generating products. These include order book trading fees, spot ticker auctions, and future Layer-1 monetization streams, creating structurally embedded buying pressure for HYPE.

Hyperliquid’s monthly trading volumes have surged more than 4x since October, driven by the intensification of onchain speculation. Looking ahead, we anticipate that a new Trump administration could further amplify volatility across crypto markets, acting as a sustained catalyst for elevated trading activity and, by extension, increased Hyperliquid revenues. With the AF in place, Hyperliquid is now able to weaponize its trading volumes. This positions Hyperliquid as one of the few top fee-generating protocols that can allocate the majority of its revenues toward tokenholder incentives.

Conclusion

Hyperliquid’s core user cohort is unique and well segmented: a community of high volume, performance and UX oriented traders. While other chains like Solana and Ethereum Mainnet have already developed an identity around its core users, we believe Hyperliquid is the only alternative L1 that has managed to form its own high-value, recurring user base. As a result, Hyperliquid owns premium real estate within the cryptoeconomy.

As the team continues to expand the L1’s functionality and integrate new protocol-level enhancements, Hyperliquid stands to further entrench its market positioning by continuously delivering value to its growing cohort of engaged traders. The introduction of new non-native assets into its deep, liquid spot market alongside its perps protocol strengthens Hyperliquid’s role as a one-stop trading ecosystem, removing friction for users who would otherwise need to split execution across multiple platforms.

Simultaneously, the launch of the HyperEVM expands Hyperliquid’s scope beyond trading, unlocking a new wave of surrounding DeFi applications built by third-party teams while preserving the competitive edge of its onchain orderbook.

Crucially, the Assistance Fund (AF) ensures that Hyperliquid’s revenue engine actively reinvests value into HYPE, a mechanism which many other DeFi protocols lack. With trading fee-derived revenues converted into continuous token accumulation, Hyperliquid has introduced a clear method for value accrual over time.

Taken together, these developments set the stage for Hyperliquid’s journey towards becoming a category-defining force in onchain finance.
